{"reasoning":"1. The essential problem in the query is a case involving state intervention in family life, particularly the removal of children from parental care due to mental health concerns, and the restriction on parental contact. The task is to traverse toward the most likely ECHR articles used in an application to the Court (i.e., substantive family rights and procedural guarantees regarding separation of children from parents).\n\nStep-by-step analysis:\n[0] EU Protocols: Rights, Procedures, and Governance - This is too general and includes a very broad set of topics (rights, procedures, governance, ratification). It is not focused on the rights at stake in the specific context of family intervention, custody, or parental separation. Thus, it is not directly relevant for identifying the most likely ECHR articles or finding the specific legal basis for state interference in family life.\n[1] EU Convention Emergency Powers - This concerns emergency derogations and suspension of obligations. The facts do not involve a national emergency, derogation, or the invocation of emergency powers, so this branch is off-topic.\n[2] EU Protocol Article 28 Committees Overview - This is about the technical functioning of committees under Article 28 of the EU Protocol, with procedural and institutional content, not touching on substantive family or child protection rights. Irrelevant.\n[3] Striking Out Applications under EU Protocol Art. 37 - This concerns procedural rules for striking out and restoring applications, not the substantive law of family separation or child welfare. Not relevant for the factual core (parental rights, state intervention).\n[4] EU Family Law Protections - This focuses exactly on parental responsibilities, spousal equality, and child welfare as defined by Protocol 7 Article 5. This is specifically about the legal rights and responsibilities in marriage, divorce, and towards children, closely matching the central legal injury (state interference in family life, custody and access, child welfare interventions). This is the most relevant, as it directly connects to substantive Convention (Protocol) articles that are typical in ECtHR applications on these facts.\n[5] Protocol 16 Article 1(3) Request Procedures - About procedure for courts asking for advisory opinions under the Convention. That is a procedural route for national courts, and not the substantive right that would be pleaded before the ECtHR in a family separation/child welfare application. Not relevant for the central legal injury.","ranking":[4,0,3,2,5,1],"relevance_scores":[[4,100],[0,25],[3,20],[2,15],[5,10],[1,5]]}
