{"reasoning":"1. Essential problem: The central legal injury concerns the interference by State authorities with parental rights and family life — specifically, the removal of children from parental care, limitations on parental access, and care orders made by social services due to mental health and child protection concerns.\n\n2. Candidate assessment:\n- Candidate [0] (Striking Out under EU Protocol Art. 37): This document concerns procedural matters related to the striking out of applications before the Court, such as the criteria for discontinuing or restoring cases, applicant intent, and case resolution options. It does not pertain to substantive rights under the European Convention (like family life, children's removal, or due process in child protection), nor does it address the merits or legal protections for parental or family rights. It is strictly about process and not relevant to the analysis of substantive human rights violations alleged in the facts.\n\nTherefore, per the relevance definition (requiring specific information needed to answer the associated question), candidate [0] is not relevant for determining which substantive Convention articles cover the legal injuries described. It would only become relevant if the question was specifically about the procedural status of an application before the ECtHR, not about substantive rights violations in child custody and protection cases.\n\n3. There are no better candidates. Thus, ranking and scoring reflect that this is the only candidate but with low substantive relevance.",
