ncated]  \n\n---\n\n## CANDIDATES\n\nHere are the candidates, each is identified by a unique `node_id` provided at the very start in [] (e.g., [0]).\n\n[0]. EU Protocol: Fundamental Rights. This subtree provides information on fundamental rights protected under the EU Protocol Section I, including the right to life, liberty and security, fair trial, privacy and family life, freedoms of religion, assembly, association, expression, and the right to marry. It answers questions about the scope, legal standards, exceptions, and permissible limitations of these rights, as well as procedural safeguards and remedies under EU law.. Key topics: right to life; liberty and security; fair trial; privacy and family life; freedom of religion; freedom of assembly and association; freedom of expression; right to marry. 6 direct children. 24 leaf passages\n\n[1]. EU Protocols: Fundamental Human Rights Protections. This subtree addresses core human rights protections under EU Protocols, including prohibitions on torture, slavery, forced labour, and the death penalty, as well as rights related to imprisonment for debt and freedom of movement. It provides legal definitions, exceptions, and specific articles relevant to these protections, supporting queries about the scope, limitations, and enforcement of these rights within EU law.. Key topics: prohibition of torture; prohibition of slavery; forced or compulsory labour; abolition of death penalty; freedom of movement; prohibition of imprisonment for debt; exceptions to rights protections; EU human rights law. 3 direct children. 16 leaf passages\n\n[2]. EU Protocol 7 Criminal Law Protections. This subtree provides information on key criminal law protections under EU Protocol 7, including the principle of legality (no punishment without law), the right of appeal in criminal matters, compensation for wrongful conviction, and double jeopardy protections. It addresses questions about legal certainty, retroactivity, appeals processes, compensation standards, and safeguards against being tried or punished twice for the same offense within the EU legal framework.. Key topics: principle of legality; retroactive criminal law; right of appeal; wrongful conviction compensation; double jeopardy; EU Protocol 7; criminal proceedings; legal safeguards. 4 direct children. 12 leaf passages\n\n[3]. EU Protocols: Aliens' Rights and Expulsion. This subtree covers legal provisions in EU Protocols regarding the rights and restrictions of aliens, including political activity limitations, protections against expulsion, and procedural safeguards for expulsion. It can answer questions about the legal status of aliens in the EU, specific articles governing expulsion and entry, and the rights of nationals versus aliens under EU law.. Key topics: EU Protocol Article 16; political activity restrictions for aliens; expulsion of aliens; collective expulsion prohibition; entry rights for nationals; procedural safeguards for expulsion; public order and national security exceptions. 3 direct children. 9 leaf passages\n\n[4]. EU Protocols: Education & Elections. This subtree covers the EU Protocols related to the right to education and the right to free elections. It provides information on legal protections for education, including parental rights and religious/philosophical convictions, as well as standards and obligations for free and fair legislative elections within the EU. Useful for queries about EU human rights protocols, education rights, and electoral standards.. Key topics: EU Protocol to Article 2; right to education; parental rights in education; religious/philosophical convictions; EU Protocol Article 3; right to free elections; election procedures; legislative election standards. 2 direct children. 4 leaf passages\n\n\n\n---\n\n## YOUR EVALUATION TASK\n1.  First, identify the essential problem in the query.\n2.  Think step by step to reason about why each candidate is relevant or irrelevant (based on the relevance definition). Provide this analysis in the `reasoning` field.\n3.  Rank these passages based on their relevance to the query. Provide your ranking in the `ranking` field.\n4.  Assign a relevance score from 0 to 100 (based on the relevance definition and the ranking). Provide relevances in the `relevance_scores` field.\n\n---\n\n## OUTPUT FORMAT\nYou must provide your response as a single, clean JSON object. The JSON should have three keys: `reasoning`, `ranking`, and `relevance_scores`.\n\n* `reasoning`: This must be a **string**.\n* `ranking`: This must be an **array of integers** representing the order of the candidates.\n* `relevance_scores`: This must be an **array of arrays** where each inner array contains [node_id, relevance_score]. For example: [[0, 85], [1, 92], [2, 73]].\n\n---\n\nPrompt ID: 2636880 (Ignore this, it is just for watermarking purposes)\n\n## YOUR RESPONSE\n"
