{"reasoning":"1. Essential problem: The facts describe state intervention in family life, especially the removal of children due to concerns about a parent's mental health and the child welfare authorities' actions (emergency and normal care orders, restrictions on access, etc). The central legal injury alleged relates to the interference with the right to respect for private and family life under the European Convention on Human Rights, as well as potential procedural defects in the way care orders were made and access was restricted.\n\n2. Candidate evaluation:\n- [0] EU Protocol: Fundamental Rights. This subtree explicitly lists 'privacy and family life' among its key topics and covers the right to family life, likely corresponding to Article 8 of the ECHR, which is central to the facts (removal of children, access restrictions, and state intervention in family matters). This is directly on point for the alleged interference.\n- [1] EU Protocols: Fundamental Human Rights Protections. This subtree concerns the prohibition of torture, slavery, forced labour, and similar protections. While child welfare and state care decisions should avoid cruel or degrading treatment, there are no allegations in the facts of torture or inhuman treatment; the injuries are about family life, not the topics listed here.\n- [2] EU Protocol 7 Criminal Law Protections. The dispute does not involve criminal trial rights, wrongful conviction, or double jeopardy. None of the facts relate to criminal law safeguards.\n- [3] EU Protocols: Aliens' Rights and Expulsion. This subtree deals with the rights of aliens and expulsion procedures. The applicants are not aliens nor is there any expulsion; rather, the issues concern social care, child removal, and family integrity.\n- [4] EU Protocols: Education & Elections. This node covers the right to education and free elections. While there may be some distant, speculative connection in exceptional cases (e.g., if family life removal affects educational rights), the facts, as presented, are focused on family integrity, not education or elections.\n\nSummary: Node [0] is the only candidate subtree that covers the right to private and family life, which is the central guarantee engaged in cases about the removal of children from parents. The others are either off-topic or would be relevant only in rare, more extreme circumstances not present in these facts.","ranking":[0,4,1,2,3],"relevance_scores":[[0,100],[4,20],[1,10],[2,5],[3,5]]}
