ncated]  \n\n---\n\n## CANDIDATES\n\nHere are the candidates, each is identified by a unique `node_id` provided at the very start in [] (e.g., [0]).\n\n[0]. Remedies and Dispute Resolution under EU/ECHR Protocols. This subtree provides information on legal remedies, compensation, and dispute resolution mechanisms under the EU and ECHR Protocols. It covers the right to an effective remedy (Art. 13), friendly settlements (Art. 39), just satisfaction/compensation (Art. 41), and the exclusion of alternative dispute settlement methods (Art. 55). Useful for questions about enforcement of rights, procedures for resolving human rights disputes, compensation for violations, and limitations on dispute resolution avenues.. Key topics: EU Protocol Article 13; effective remedy; friendly settlements (Article 39); just satisfaction (Article 41); compensation for rights violations; exclusion of alternative dispute settlement (Article 55); European Court of Human Rights procedures; Committee of Ministers supervision. 4 direct children. 11 leaf passages\n\n[1]. EU Protocol Court Procedures and Jurisdiction. This subtree addresses procedural and jurisdictional aspects of the European Court of Human Rights under the EU Protocol and Convention. It covers Chamber and Grand Chamber decision-making, admissibility criteria for applications, procedures for relinquishing and referring cases, the Court's jurisdictional scope, and specific procedural rules under Articles 34 and 38. Use this subtree to answer questions about how cases are admitted, transferred, examined, and decided, as well as the legal bases and criteria for these actions.. Key topics: Chamber decisions and admissibility; Grand Chamber powers and referrals; Relinquishment of jurisdiction; Court jurisdiction under EU Protocol; ECHR admissibility criteria; Procedural rules (Articles 34 & 38); Inter-State and individual applications. 6 direct children. 26 leaf passages\n\n[2]. EU/ECHR Judgment Procedures and Execution. This subtree addresses the procedures, requirements, and enforcement mechanisms for judgments under the EU Protocol and the European Convention on Human Rights. It covers when and how judgments become final, the publication and reasoning of judgments, the possibility of separate opinions, and the binding force and execution of judgments, including the roles of the Grand Chamber, Committee of Ministers, and High Contracting Parties. Use this subtree to answer questions about judgment finality, publication, reasoning requirements, and enforcement processes.. Key topics: EU Protocol judgment finality; Grand Chamber referrals; Publication of judgments; Article 45 reasons for judgments; Separate judicial opinions; ECHR Article 46 execution; Committee of Ministers supervision; Enforcement of ECHR judgments. 3 direct children. 14 leaf passages\n\n[3]. EU Court Financials and Judicial Protections. Covers financial responsibilities and legal protections related to the EU judiciary, including which entities fund the Court under Article 50 of the EU Protocol and the privileges and immunities granted to EU judges under Article 51 and related Council of Europe statutes. Useful for queries about court expenditure, financial accountability, and judicial immunities within the EU legal framework.. Key topics: EU Protocol Article 50; EU Protocol Article 51; Court expenditure; Financial responsibility; Privileges of EU judges; Immunities of EU judges; Council of Europe statutes. 2 direct children. 4 leaf passages\n\n\n\n---\n\n## YOUR EVALUATION TASK\n1.  First, identify the essential problem in the query.\n2.  Think step by step to reason about why each candidate is relevant or irrelevant (based on the relevance definition). Provide this analysis in the `reasoning` field.\n3.  Rank these passages based on their relevance to the query. Provide your ranking in the `ranking` field.\n4.  Assign a relevance score from 0 to 100 (based on the relevance definition and the ranking). Provide relevances 