ncated]  \n\n---\n\n## CANDIDATES\n\nHere are the candidates, each is identified by a unique `node_id` provided at the very start in [] (e.g., [0]).\n\n[0]. EU Protocol Art. 13: Effective Remedy. Information about the right to an effective remedy under Article 13 of the EU Protocol, including the scope, requirements, and application of this right when rights and freedoms are violated, even by officials. Useful for questions on legal remedies, enforcement of rights, and obligations of national authorities under the Convention.. Key topics: EU Protocol Article 13; right to an effective remedy; national authority obligations; violations by officials; enforcement of rights; legal remedies under EU law. 2 direct children. 2 leaf passages\n\n[1]. EU Protocol Art. 39 Friendly Settlements. This subtree covers the procedures and provisions of Article 39 of the EU Protocol regarding friendly settlements in human rights cases. It addresses how and when the Court facilitates settlements, the confidentiality of proceedings, the process for striking cases from the docket, and the role of the Committee of Ministers in supervising settlement execution.. Key topics: Article 39 EU Protocol; friendly settlements; European Court of Human Rights; confidential proceedings; case removal procedures; Committee of Ministers supervision. 5 direct children. 5 leaf passages\n\n[2]. ECHR Protocol Article 41: Just Satisfaction. This subtree addresses the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) Protocol Article 41, focusing on the concept of 'just satisfaction'—the compensation or remedy provided by the Court when a violation is found and domestic law offers only partial reparation. It covers the legal basis, conditions, and application of just satisfaction in ECHR proceedings.. Key topics: ECHR Protocol Article 41; just satisfaction; remedies for violations; partial reparation; European Court of Human Rights; compensation procedures. 2 direct children. 2 leaf passages\n\n[3]. Art. 55: Exclusion of Other Dispute Settlement Methods. Covers Article 55 of the EU Protocol, detailing the exclusion of alternative dispute settlement mechanisms for disputes under the Convention. Answers questions about the prohibition on using other treaties, conventions, or declarations for dispute resolution, except by special agreement.. Key topics: Article 55; EU Protocol; exclusion of dispute settlement; alternative dispute resolution; special agreement; treaties and conventions; interpretation of the Convention. 2 direct children. 2 leaf passages\n\n\n\n---\n\n## YOUR EVALUATION TASK\n1.  First, identify the essential problem in the query.\n2.  Think step by step to reason about why each candidate is relevant or irrelevant (based on the relevance definition). Provide this analysis in the `reasoning` field.\n3.  Rank these passages based on their relevance to the query. Provide your ranking in the `ranking` field.\n4.  Assign a relevance score from 0 to 100 (based on the relevance definition and the ranking). Provide relevances in the `relevance_scores` field.\n\n---\n\n## OUTPUT FORMAT\nYou must provide your response as a single, clean JSON object. The JSON should have three keys: `reasoning`, `ranking`, and `relevance_scores`.\n\n* `reasoning`: This must be a **string**.\n* `ranking`: This must be an **array of integers** representing the order of the candidates.\n* `relevance_scores`: This must be an **array of arrays** where each inner array contains [node_id, relevance_score]. For example: [[0, 85], [1, 92], [2, 73]].\n\n---\n\nPrompt ID: 4629959 (Ignore this, it is just for watermarking purposes)\n\n## YOUR RESPONSE\n"
Response:
{"reasoning":"1. Central Legal Injury: The essential problem in the query is whether the removal of children from the parents' custody by social welfare authorities, and the restriction of access, constituted an unlawful interference with the right to respect for family life under the European Convention on Human Rights. The facts point to a state interference (removal of children, emergency placement into care, restriction of parental rights, etc.) which is the classic legal substance of Article 8 of the ECHR (right to respect for private and family life), possibly with procedural elements (right to a remedy). However, Article 8 is not listed among the candidates; the provided options are Protocol Articles 13, 39, 41, and 55.\n\n- [0] Protocol Art. 13: Effective Remedy — This article relates to the right to an effective remedy for violations of rights and freedoms under the Convention. In the context of the facts, it may be secondary (if the applicants did not have or could not access a remedy for the child removal/custody orders). It is relevant as a procedural guarantee but not the primary substantive right at issue.\n\n- [1] Protocol Art. 39: Friendly Settlements — This article is about the procedural mechanism for resolving cases by settlement before the Court, not about the substantive rights or remedies. It is not relevant to the legal injury described in the facts.\n\n- [2] Protocol Art. 41: Just Satisfaction — This provision addresses compensation if a violation is found, assuming rights have already been established as breached. It is thus not the central substantive route, but may become relevant if a violation is found. Its direct applicability in selecting the leaf articles most relevant to the legal injury is secondary.\n\n- [3] Art. 55: Exclusion of Other Dispute Settlement Methods — This is a jurisdictional provision excluding other routes for disputes covered under the Convention. It does not speak to the substance or procedural remedy for the legal injury. It is background material only.\n\nConclusion: Among the candidates, Article 13 (effective remedy) is most relevant as a secondary/procedural guarantee in this context, whereas the others are either procedural provisions (settlement, jurisdiction) or only activated after a violation is found (just satisfaction). None are the primary substantive right (Article 8), but Article 13 would be the most closely tied to potential complaint about lack of remedy for the removal of the children.","ranking":[0,2,1,3],"relevance_scores":[[0,60],[2,25],[1,10],[3,0]]}
