{"reasoning":"The essential legal problem in the query concerns the interference by state authorities with parental custody and access to children based on psychiatric and child welfare concerns. The ECtHR would primarily examine if there was a justified and proportionate interference with family life protected by Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights. However, all the presented candidate nodes relate only to provisions of various EU Protocol Articles—primarily those found in EU law, not the classic rights-based articles of the ECHR (e.g., Article 8: right to respect for private and family life, Article 6: right to a fair trial, Article 5: right to liberty and security) which would normally be the most directly applicable to the core problem presented. \n\nReviewing the candidates:\n- [0] covers specific articles from EU Protocol (Article 5, 30, 34), but Article 5 in the Protocol context does not address family life or state intervention in child custody. Article 34 concerns individual applications and procedural rights—not the substantive family law rights in question. This is only tangentially relevant if the case is about access to a legal remedy and recourse to the ECtHR.\n- [1] covers Protocol Articles 45 and 47—these are largely procedural and unrelated to the substance of parental rights or state intervention in families.\n- [2] focuses on Article 34 (right of individual application)—procedurally relevant as it allows submission of applications to the Court, but not substantively relevant to the legal injury (interference in family life).\n- [3] and [4] focus on Article 56 (and Protocol 4 Article 56), which are about the territorial application of the Convention—not substantively relevant here.\n- [5] contains general references to Protocol 7 (Articles 4 and 15), which concern procedural guarantees regarding expulsion of aliens and derogation in times of emergency—neither is relevant to state removal of children or parental access.\n\nTherefore, none of the candidates directly provide substantive Convention articles corresponding to the main legal injury (interference in family life, right to respect for private/family life under Art. 8 ECHR). The closest relevance is [2] (procedural right to bring a claim under Article 34), with some tangential relevance in [0] (if Article 34 is presented there) and the rest are irrelevant.","ranking":[2,0,1,5,3,4],"relevance_scores":[[0,20],[1,10],[2,30],[3,5],[4,5],[5,10]]}
