{
  "reasoning": "The central legal injury in the case facts is the removal of children (M. and J.) from the custody of their mother, K., and restrictions on her access to her children, all by state authorities due to concerns about her mental health and the children's welfare. Under ECtHR jurisprudence, the most directly relevant Convention right engaged is Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR), which protects the right to respect for private and family life. Given the provided candidates, candidate [1] contains the substantive provision in Article 8(1) that establishes the general right to family life and would be directly used in an application. Candidate [2] contains Article 8(2), which specifies when state interference can be justified. Both [1] and [2] are highly relevant because together they form the substantive and justificatory legal tests the Court uses. Candidate [0] is just a heading or title for Article 8 and does not, by itself, contribute specific legal content. As this task requires consideration of passages in isolation, the text of [1] and [2] each provides key legal information: [1] frames the right, and [2] frames the state's justified limits on that right, directly mapping onto the established facts involving interference with family life and the possible justifications invoked by the state (child protection, health, etc.).",
  "ranking": [1, 2, 0],
  "relevance_scores": [
    [0, 5],   	[
