{"reasoning":"1. Essential problem: The facts describe a situation where state authorities intervened in the family life of K. and her children, including placing the children in care and restricting parental access. The central legal injury concerns state interference with the right to family life, but among the provided candidates, all relate only to Article 5 (Right to liberty and security), not Article 8 (Right to respect for private and family life), which would have been the centripetal article in this case. However, state orders such as compulsory psychiatric hospitalization and emergency care of family members could engage Article 5 if they constitute deprivations of liberty. \n\n2. Candidate analysis:\n- [0] Title only. It does not contain specific information, so it is irrelevant.\n- [1] Contains the full text of Article 5(1), laying out exhaustive admissible grounds for deprivation of liberty, including the lawful detention of persons of unsound mind and minors for educational supervision. This text is directly relevant, as both K.'s psychiatric detentions and M. and J.'s removals to children's homes are factually central, and the lawful basis for any deprivations of liberty must be determined by these criteria. Thus, this passage substantively contributes to analyzing the lawfulness of such deprivation.\n- [2] Contains Article 5(2), which concerns the procedural right to be informed of the reasons for arrest/detention and any charge. The facts suggest the applicants were notified in writing after the decisions, but not heard prior. This provision could be relevant if the applicants claim lack of information or notification of deprivation of liberty, though the central issue is less about notification and more about the lawfulness and process.\n- [3] Contains Article 5(4), the right to speedy court review of detention. The applicants did not appeal but the provision is fundamentally relevant for potential complaints about the lawfulness of psychiatric or child detention and available remedies.\n- [4] Article 5(5) gives a right to compensation for lawful detention. This is only engaged if there has already been a violation established under previous sections, so it is secondary rather than primary.\n\nRanking: Article 5(1) is primary, defining whether there was a justified deprivation of liberty; Article 5(4) is also primary, securing recourse against unlawful detention. Article 5(2) is less central—procedural safeguard, not legal basis itself. Article 5(5) is very secondary. Article [0], just the title, contains no actionable information.","ranking":[1,3,2,4,0],"relevance_scores":[[0,5],[1,95],[2,55],[3,85],[4,20]]}
