{"reasoning":"First, the essential problem in the user query concerns the forced and emergency removal of children from their mother, limitations on parental access, and procedural aspects around public care – in short, state interference with family life. This falls squarely within Article 8 of the Convention (Right to respect for private and family life), but none of the provided candidates are Article 8 or other central Convention articles. \n\n- [0] Protocol 4: This protocol mostly covers issues like prohibition of imprisonment for debt, freedom of movement, etc. Its provisions do not directly address child custody, public care, or family life interferences. Given the specifics of the facts, Protocol 4 is irrelevant.\n- [1] Protocol 12: This protocol introduces a general prohibition of discrimination. There is no evidence in the facts of discrimination being the central legal issue — the core is about interference with family life and procedural rights. Thus, Protocol 12 is not substantively relevant to the main injury.\n- [2] Protocol 13: This protocol abolishes the death penalty in all circumstances. The case has nothing to do with capital punishment, so this candidate is entirely irrelevant.\n\nAll candidates are only Protocol titles and do not provide any substantive provision text that could answer the primary query. Moreover, none of the provided protocols directly or substantively address the critical Convention rights in play (such as Article 8). Therefore, none would be considered relevant under the provided definition, and all receive the lowest scores, with no meaningful order other than their listing.","ranking":[0,1,2],"relevance_scores":[[0,0],[1,0],[2,0]]}
