{"reasoning":"1. Essential Problem: The core legal issue in the facts involves state interference with family life—specifically, the removal of children from their mother and limitations on parental access due to concerns about her mental health and social welfare concerns. The relevant ECHR article is Article 8 (right to respect for private and family life) and, in some cases, Article 6 (fair trial) or Article 5 (liberty/security) only if detention is involved. However, only the provided candidate documents can be considered.\n\nAnalysis of passages:\n[0] EU Protocol Section I Art. 5 – Only a title. Does not contain actual provision text, so does not substantially answer the query.\n[1] EU Protocol Section I Art. 5(1) – Presumably contains the provision text, but the actual content is not provided in the passage (just a title/identifier). Therefore, this is not useful on its own.\n[2] EU Protocol Section II Art. 34 – This is just a title/reference to an article, without any provision text. Does not directly answer the query.\n[3] EU Protocol Section II Art. 30 – Another article title/reference only, with no provision text included.\n[4] EU Protocol Section II Art. 30(1) – Same as above, only a reference and does not include any actual informative content.\n\nNone of the candidate passages provide the actual text or content of the articles or protocol provisions. As such, all are at best section headings or identifiers, with no substantive content supporting an answer to the user's query (which seeks not just identification of the article, but the semantic explanation and the provision text itself). Therefore, by the strict relevance definition, all are very weak candidates.\n\nRanking: Since all are only references, their relevance is effectively equal and minimal; I will order them as per node_id for the sake of structure.","ranking":[0,1,2,3,4],"relevance_scores":[[0,5],[1,5],[2,5],[3,5],[4,5]]}
