{"reasoning":"1. Central Issue: The user's query, and the facts provided, focus on removal of children from parental care, state intervention in family life, and procedural/protective defects around these actions. The relevant ECtHR legal concepts mainly concern the right to respect for family life (Article 8 ECHR) and possibly procedural rights, with a focus on concrete child protection/state interference articles at the leaf node level. \n2. Passage Assessment:\n- [0]: This passage is administrative and procedural, stating only that certain Protocol articles (1–4) are regarded as additional Articles to the Convention, with no substantive or specific rights or law provisions—no direct substantive information regarding removal of children, family life, or remedies. \n- [1]: This passage is only a generic, truncated procedural note that additional Protocol articles are part of the Convention. It contains no substantive law or provision, and gives no information directly bearing on the application's injuries or central legal complaint.\n- [2]: Like the others, this is a procedural cross-reference integrating Protocol 12 Articles 1 and 2 as additional Convention articles, without detailing any actual right or provision. Not only does it not include legal detail, it does not mention family life, child protection, or state intervention.\n- [3]: This is a fragment—not even a full sentence—merely echoing that Protocol articles are additional, with no substantive content relevant to the case.\n- [4]: This passage recites that Protocol 16 Articles 1–5 are added as articles to the Convention, and briefly refers to formal treaty actions, but provides absolutely no substantive law content on the underlying family/child removal issues. \n\nAll candidates contain only bureaucratic cross-references about Protocols being added to the Convention—they do not set out rights, protections, procedures, or substantive articles relating to family life, removal of children, child protection, or remedies. None provide an answer as required by the user's query (traversing toward the most relevant ECHR/Protocol articles on child removal and family rights). All are therefore entirely non-substantive for the legal question at issue.","ranking":[0,1,2,3,4],"relevance_scores":[[0,0],[1,0],[2,0],[3,0],[4,0]]}
